          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>2 fol.; Writing surface: parchment; Shelfmark: Islamic Arabic 1572a; Lines per page: 22-30; Dimensions: 245 x 333 mm; Qurʾānic Text: Q              Q 18:17-31, Q 19:91 - Q 20:40; Script style: ḥiǧāzī/kūfī B.Ia; Estimated date of production: 632-660 (?).</p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>The call number "Islamic Arabic 1572a" consists of two folios, formerly fol. 1 and fol. 7 of a combined manuscript Islamic Arabic 1572. The parchment of Islamic Arabic 1572a was dated by the University of Oxford (Radiocarbon Accelerator Unit) by C14 measurement: 1456, 21 BP (= before present), according to the calibration of Intcal 2020 this corresponds to the period 578-646 CE (95.4%). Islamic Arabic 1572a, together with 16 fol. of <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/158/page/71r?sura=10&amp;verse=35">Arabe 328 (c)</ref>, once belonged to one Qur'anic codex, while the Saint Petersburg fragment <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/333/page/1r?sura=2&amp;verse=269">Marcel 17</ref> probably comes from the same codex as <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/281/page/2r?sura=4&amp;verse=153">1572b</ref> and a fragment in the Museum for Islamic Art (Doha, Qatar). Islamic Arabic 1572 was acquired by Alphonse Mingana in the Middle East in the 1920s when, sponsored by the chocolate manufacturer Edward Cadbury, he made three trips to the Middle East to buy oriental manuscripts: Two trips in 1924 and 1925 to Lebanon, Syria and Iraq, and a third trip in 1929 to Egypt. Since <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/158/page/71r?sura=10&amp;verse=35">Arabe 328 (c)</ref> and <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/333/page/1r?sura=2&amp;verse=269">Marcel 17</ref> were acquired from Jean-Louis Asselin de Cherville (d. 1822) in Cairo, and since both originally are from codices to which 1572a and 1572b respectively once belonged, it is likely that Mingana acquired the "Birmingham fragments" during his trip to Egypt in 1929. Like most early Qur'ān manuscripts of the Bibliothèque nationale de France and the Marcel collection, 1572a and 1572b probably originate from the store room of the ʿAmr-ibn-al-ʿĀṣ Mosque in al-Fusṭāṭ (Old Cairo).</p>
            </summary>
